Bring a large #saucepan{} of water with @salt{1/2%tsp} to the boil for the potatoes.

Meanwhile, trim the @carrot{1}, then quarter lengthways (no need to peel). Chop widthways into small pieces.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{3} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Peel and slice the @potatoes{450} into 1cm thick rounds.

Once boiling, add the potato slices to the water and simmer until tender, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{1%drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat.

Once hot, add the @British beef mince{240} and carrot. Fry until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break the mince up as it cooks, then drain and discard any excess fat.

Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince. It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once browned, add half the garlic to the beef and cook for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @tomato passata{1}, @red wine stock paste{28} and @sugar{1/2} for the sauce. Lower the heat and simmer until thickened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Meanwhile, preheat your #grill{} to high.

Once the potatoes are cooked, reserve some of the potato water, then carefully drain in a #colander{}.

Wipe out the (now empty) saucepan and return to medium heat with a drizzle of @oil{1%drizzle}. Add the remaining garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @creme fraiche{150}, @chicken stock paste{10} and @reserved potato water{75}. Bring to the boil, then remove from the heat. Season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Once the beef mixture is ready, spoon it into an appropriately sized #ovenproof dish{}.

Carefully lay the cooked potato slices in layers over the top, then pour over the creamy sauce. Sprinkle over the @grated hard Italian style cheese{20}.

Grill on the top shelf of your #oven{} until golden, ~{6-7%minutes}.

> TIP: Put the dish onto a baking tray to catch any drips.

Once ready, share the cottage dauphinoise pie out between your plates and tuck in. Enjoy!